<emphasis id="E3ED26401B0DFFC1F7BDF69EF749F4CC" bold="true" box="[2089,2265,2799,2832]" pageId="19" pageNumber="530">Distribution.</emphasis>
NW Argentina, known only from the type locality near Tinogasta.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="9983A9D91B0DFFC1F7BDF74FF7A8F3AC" pageId="19" pageNumber="530" type="description">
<paragraph id="D126FA521B0DFFC1F7BDF74FF7A8F3AC" blockId="19.[2089,2683,2563,2989]" lastBlockId="19.[1474,2681,2995,3459]" pageId="19" pageNumber="530">
<emphasis id="E3ED26401B0DFFC1F7BDF74FF6B8F483" bold="true" box="[2089,2344,2878,2911]" pageId="19" pageNumber="530">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Total length 302 mm, tail 97 mm, all measurements from the type specimen (a male). No specific data are available for body weight. The Puntilla Tuco-tuco is relatively large. It is easily identified by uniform pale color, long tail, narrow skull, and large bullae. It is also easily differentiated from the two geographically closest species: the smaller Foch’s Tuco-tuco (
<taxonomicName id="169981D11B0DFFC1FA46F05CF9A3F396" authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1919" box="[1490,1587,3117,3146]" class="Mammalia" family="Ctenomyidae" genus="Ctenomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="19" pageNumber="531" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fochi">C. fochi</taxonomicName>
) and the Catamarca Tuco-tuco (
<taxonomicName id="169981D11B0DFFC1F863F05CF7E6F396" authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1919" box="[2039,2166,3117,3146]" class="Mammalia" family="Ctenomyidae" genus="Ctenomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="19" pageNumber="530" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="knighti">C. knighti</taxonomicName>
) that is much darker and has shorter tail, larger teeth, and broader frontal region.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
